    <!-- PEERAGE -->
    <div class="article-section" id="peerage">
      <h2>The Peerage of the Realm</h2>

      <div class="peerage-note">
        <p>Below the twelve <a href="#great-houses" class="wikilink">Royal Houses</a>, the lands of Ormandia are subdivided among a broader peerage of <strong>Dukes</strong>, <strong>Margraves</strong>, <strong>Counts</strong>, and <strong>Barons</strong> (and their female equivalents — Duchesses, Margravines, Countesses, and Baronesses), each owing fealty, taxation, and in most cases levied troops to the ruling house of their country. None hold a seat on the High Council in their own right, but several of the figures below wield influence — through wealth, military command, arcane talent, or sheer longevity in office — that rivals the lesser Royal Houses themselves.</p>
        <p><strong>Margraves</strong> occupy a special position within this hierarchy. Their titles are traditionally hereditary military commands over the Realm's border marches — the Greymantis frontier, the Thornwall, and the western archipelago among them — and carry standing martial authority unusual for the peerage, granted in exchange for the burden, expense, and danger of frontier defense.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="rank-heading" id="dukes">Dukes &amp; Duchesses</h3>

      <div class="noble-card">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Duchess</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Maren Ashgrove</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Duchess of Ashgrove, Warden of the Deepwood Archives</span>
        </div>
        <p>A cousin of <a href="#ashenvale" class="wikilink">Queen Seraphine Ashenvale</a>, Duchess Maren holds one of the most quietly consequential offices in the Realm: stewardship of the wards, vaults, and reading-halls of the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Deepwood Archives</a> beneath Ashencrown. Reclusive even by Ashenvale standards, she is said to have read more of the Archive's restricted texts than any living person save the Queen herself — a fact that has not gone unnoticed by <a href="#ironwall" class="wikilink">House Ironwall</a>'s agents.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>House Ashenvale (cadet line)</span>
          <span>Ashenvale</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="noble-card">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Duke</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Tobias Vane</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Duke of the Ember Reaches</span>
        </div>
        <p>A cadet member of <a href="#embervane" class="wikilink">House Embervane</a>, Duke Tobias governs Emberfall's volatile eastern border with the nomadic <a href="cultures.html#emberkin" class="wikilink">Emberkin</a>. Where his predecessors met Emberkin incursions with cavalry, Tobias has spent the last decade building an unprecedented (and, among Emberfall's traditionalists, deeply controversial) network of trade agreements and seasonal grazing rights with the clans — a policy that has reduced border raids by a reported two-thirds, but which his critics at the Char Citadel court characterize as appeasement.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>House Embervane (cadet line)</span>
          <span>Emberfall</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="noble-card">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Duchess</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Briallen Thornecroft</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Duchess of Thornwood</span>
        </div>
        <p>The eldest daughter of <a href="#thornecroft" class="wikilink">Lord Aldous Thornecroft</a> and the current holder of Thorneshire's traditional heir-apparent duchy, Briallen is widely regarded as the most politically capable of Aldous's three children — and, by the same measure, the one least favored by Thorneshire's deeply traditionalist court, which has historically resisted female succession to the head of House Thornecroft despite the Compact's Fifth Article. Her management of Thornwood's estates is, by every available measure, the most profitable of any ducal holding in Thorneshire.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>House Thornecroft</span>
          <span>Thorneshire</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="rank-heading" id="margraves">Margraves &amp; Margravines (Marcher Lords)</h3>

      <div class="noble-card margrave">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Margravine</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Isolde Greymantle</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Margravine of the Greymantis March</span>
        </div>
        <p>Hereditary guardian of the northern passes through the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Greymantis Range</a>, Margravine Isolde commands the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Greymantle Wardens</a>, an order of mountain rangers tasked with watching for incursions from the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Far Northlands</a>. The Greymantle title has been held by the same family for over twenty generations — longer, by a considerable margin, than any Royal House has held an unbroken line — a fact Margravine Isolde is not shy about mentioning at High Council functions.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>Sworn to House Valdenmyr</span>
          <span>Valdenmere</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="noble-card margrave">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Margrave</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Cedric Thornwall</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Margrave of the Thornwall March</span>
        </div>
        <p>Warden of Thorneshire's eastern border, directly beneath the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Thornwall</a> itself, Margrave Cedric holds what is by reputation the least desirable title in the Realm's peerage — a post few noble families have ever competed for, and which the Thornecrofts have historically assigned to whichever cousin proved least useful at court. Cedric, by most accounts, has taken the assignment more seriously than any Thornwall Margrave in living memory, commissioning the first formal survey of the Thornwall's base in over a century, the findings of which have not been made public.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>Sworn to House Thornecroft</span>
          <span>Thorneshire</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="noble-card margrave" id="saltmere">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Margrave</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Bryndor Saltmere</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Margrave of the Saltmere Reaches</span>
        </div>
        <p>Overseer of Craedmoor's western archipelago borderlands and the Crown's principal point of contact with the <a href="cultures.html#garroni" class="wikilink">Garroni</a> holds, Margrave Bryndor occupies a position built almost entirely on studied ambiguity. His office maintains a decades-long unwritten understanding with several Garroni Tide-Mothers — tolerance of Garroni autonomy in exchange for Garroni cooperation against raiders who do not observe the customary courtesies. Neither the High Council nor any Tide-Moot has ever been asked to formally acknowledge this arrangement, and Margrave Bryndor has made it a point of personal policy never to write any part of it down.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>Sworn to House Merwynd</span>
          <span>Craedmoor</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="rank-heading" id="counts">Counts, Countesses, Barons &amp; Baronesses</h3>

      <div class="noble-card lesser">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Count</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Roderin Vale</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Count of Valehollow, Lord Treasurer of the Compact</span>
        </div>
        <p>As Lord Treasurer, Count Roderin oversees the Compact's shared treasury and the minting of the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Golden Stag</a> from his seat at Valehollow, a small but immensely wealthy county owing to its proximity to Valdenmere's mints. The office of Lord Treasurer is not hereditary, but the Vale family has held it for four consecutive appointments — long enough that several other counts have begun, only half-jokingly, to refer to it as such.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>Sworn to House Valdenmyr</span>
          <span>Valdenmere</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="noble-card lesser">
        <div class="noble-header">
          <span class="noble-rank">Baroness</span>
          <span class="noble-name">Wren Tallow</span>
          <span class="noble-title">Baroness of Tallowfield</span>
        </div>
        <p>The lowest-ranked noble of any note in the Realm, Baroness Wren governs a modest farming county in Thorneshire — and is, nonetheless, among the most discussed figures in recent Ormandian politics. When her tenants organized in protest of grain taxation in the lead-up to what many feared would become a second <a href="#" class="wikilink">Thorneshire Dispute</a>, Baroness Wren negotiated directly with the protest leaders rather than calling for Thornecroft levies, producing the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Tallowfield Accord</a> — a settlement now studied at the Valdenmere Academy of Statecraft as a model of de-escalation, and viewed with considerable suspicion by Lord Aldous Thornecroft's more conservative advisors.</p>
        <div class="noble-footer">
          <span>Sworn to House Thornecroft</span>
          <span>Thorneshire</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="divider">⚜ ✦ ⚜</div>
    </div>

    <div class="article-section" id="succession">
      <h2>Succession Law</h2>
      <p>Succession within the Royal Houses is governed by the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Compact's Fifth Article</a>, which establishes primogeniture as the default inheritance model across the Realm — meaning the eldest child, regardless of gender, inherits the title and primary seat. This represented a significant reform from earlier practice, in which succession laws varied wildly by house and country, a source of frequent conflict.</p>
      <p>Exceptions exist. Houses may petition the High Council to override the Compact's default succession rules if there is documented evidence of the heir's incapacity, criminal conviction, or declared treachery. The process is slow, contentious, and expensive — by design.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="article-section" id="alliances">
      <h2>Current Alliances &amp; Rivalries</h2>
      <p>As of the current political moment, the primary alliance structures are: the <strong>Valdenmyr–Silvermoore Accord</strong> (arcane and political cooperation), the <strong>Thornecroft–Ashenvale Marriage Bond</strong> (now in its second generation), and the informal <strong>Maritime Compact</strong> between House Merwynd and a coalition of lesser coastal lords. The primary active rivalry is between Houses Ironwall and Thornecroft, with the Ashenvale–Ironwall tension over the Deepwood Archives a secondary but potentially more dangerous friction point.</p>
      <p>Watchers of Ormandian court politics note with some alarm that the three Great Houses have not convened a joint private council in over a decade — an unusually long gap that some interpret as quiet disunity within the Realm's foundational structure.</p>
